Latin America in the Fight Against COVID-19
São Paulo/Santiago/Bogotá/Mexico City – The COVID-19 pandemic is a shock of unprecedented size and unknown duration.
The consequences are already catastrophic.
If we do not meet this crisis with decisive action, it could become the tragically worst episode in Latin American history.
So far, political reactions in our region have been very diverse.
Some governments reacted quickly and made the protection of public health their top priority.
And yet others downplayed the dangers of the pandemic, gave their citizens false information, and ignored not only scientific research but also the advice of their own experts.
These leaders chose populist and divisive policies amidst the tragedy.
Latin America's top priority must be to keep the number of deaths as low as possible.
The politicians must focus on improving healthcare systems, equipping hospitals with resources, temporarily utilizing idle infrastructure such as hotels or convention centers, and significantly increasing testing capacities.
Furthermore, Latin American states must reject export controls on medical supplies and other vital resources and advocate for additional resources for the World Health Organization (WHO) – in contrast to US President Donald Trump, who made a callous decision to freeze around $500 million in contributions to the WHO.
We need stronger global cooperation among health authorities to increase testing capacities, treat and isolate patients, and develop treatment options and vaccines – in order to ultimately end the pandemic.
The economic shock is enormous: Not only has Latin America's domestic production been interrupted, but the countries there also suffer from declining export volumes and prices, income losses due to missing tourism, fewer foreign remittances, and significant capital outflows.
The supply shock in large parts of the economy could trigger a contraction spiral together with the collapse of demand.
To prevent this, bold steps are needed to safeguard household incomes.
This means transferring support to the crisis victims, including informal and independent workers who do not have access to employment subsidies or unemployment insurance.
Also relief for businesses is important.
Subsidies that help companies pay wages and benefits protect both the companies and their employees during the crisis. Thus, they are crucial for a swift economic recovery after the pandemic.
If the flood of bankruptcies is not prevented, the next victims of the pandemic could be the banks.
And at this point, then the payment system – and with it the entire economy – is at risk.
Many companies, especially small and medium-sized ones, will suffer significant revenue losses during the crisis.
Without support, the liquidity shortfall will soon turn into a solvency problem.
Tax deferrals, payment extensions, and subsidized loans will not be sufficient.
This emergency requires not only unprecedented credit guarantees by the governments to ensure that banks continue to lend, but also temporary regulatory changes to promote credit expansion.
Even well-capitalized and managed state banks can play a leading role in this.
Overall, while the measures will vary by country, extraordinary budget resources will likely be necessary everywhere to accelerate the recovery.
The governments must stimulate employment and economic activities without worsening the risks to health.
The problem is that the fiscal space in Latin America today is even narrower than it was after the global financial crisis of 2008.
Also, budget pressures in less priority areas need to be alleviated through budget adjustments.
There is a risk of a downgrade in creditworthiness, which can, however, be mitigated by the government's promise to correct the higher budget deficits within an appropriate timeframe.
However, external support for budgets and balance sheets is urgently needed, particularly for the smaller and less developed Latin American countries.
Both private companies and states facing higher deficits will likely also deteriorate the balance sheets of the countries.
The recent capital outflows from emerging markets – one of the greatest reversals in the history of financial markets – exacerbate the problem further.
The resulting currency devaluations can have a destabilizing effect.
In many economies of the region, the only way to cope with these mutually reinforcing shocks will be to receive much more external support.
Here the International Monetary Fund (IMF) plays a decisive role.
He must address the short-term currency and budget needs of the countries and continue to support the economies in this crisis, whose duration is highly uncertain.
He needs more resources and the ability to pay them quickly.
The Latin American governments should jointly call for a renewal of the global reserve currency of the IMF – special drawing rights, which should amount to a billion SDRs.
Although SDRs are allocated to member countries based on their IMF quotas, an unequal allocation could be achieved by establishing a common pool under the supervision of the fund.
Additionally, the IMF could create the necessary capacity through an immediate doubling of new credit lines to cover the expected strong credit demand.
And finally, the fund must improve access to low-threshold tools with quick disbursement – such as its Rapid Financing Instrument – or introduce new credit facilities for the pandemic, as traditional IMF credit programs are not being approved in a timely manner.
Major reserve-currency issuing central banks can help by expanding access to currency swaps—either directly or indirectly through the IMF or the International Monetary Fund (IMF), which can channel liquidity to central banks.
Domestically, central banks must use all available instruments and create new ones if necessary to provide financial markets and the economy with sufficient liquidity.
And finally, multilateral development banks (MDBs) such as the World Bank, the Inter-American Development Bank, and the Latin American CAF Development Bank must double the volume of net credit disbursements in the region and tap into highly liquid global capital markets to provide additional budget support.
In exceptional circumstances and in countries without market access, official credit provision could be supplemented by a debt haircut.
The MDBs should also provide guidelines to the countries on the different policy areas involved in crisis management, including their own estimates of the COVID-19 infection and mortality rates – especially for countries where governments downplay the health threat.
Time plays a crucial role in this.
The challenge posed by this pandemic has no precedent in recent history.
The world and the Latin American and Caribbean region cannot afford delayed or inadequate responses.
Mutual trust, transparency, and reasonableness remain the best guidelines in these uncertain times – not populism or demagogy.
The crisis must not be used as an excuse to weaken our hard-won citizen rights.
Instead, it can serve as an opportunity to strengthen democracy in Latin America and demonstrate what it can offer its citizens.
